SIMPLE: prevail
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Prevail
<hw>Pre*vail"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Prevailed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Prevailing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F.
<ets>pr⟦eacute⟧valoir</ets>, OF. <ets>prevaleir</ets>, L.
<ets>praevalere</ets>; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>valere</ets> to be
strong, able, or worth. See <er>Valiant</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
overcome; to gain the victory or superiority; to gain the advantage; to
have the upper hand, or the mastery; to succeed; -- sometimes with
<xex>over</xex> or <xex>against</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When Moses held up his hand, Israel <qex>prevailed</qex>, and when
he let down his hand, Amalek <qex>prevailed</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Ex.
xvii. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So David <qex>prevailed</qex> over the Philistine.</q> <rj><qau>1
Sam. xvii. 50.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This kingdom could never <qex>prevail</qex> against the united
power of <qex>England</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To be in force; to have effect, power, or influence;
to be predominant; to have currency or prevalence; to obtain; <as>as,
the practice <ex>prevails</ex> this day</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This custom makes the short-sighted bigots, and the warier
skeptics, as far as it <qex>prevails</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To persuade or induce; -- with <xex>on</xex>,
<xex>upon</xex>, or <xex>with</xex>; <as>as, I <ex>prevailed</ex>on him
to wait</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He was <qex>prevailed</qex> with to restrain the Earl.</q>
<rj><qau>Clarendon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Prevail</qex> upon some judicious friend to be your constant
hearer, and allow him the utmost freedom.</q>
<rj><qau>Swift.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prevailing</ent>⟦br⟧
